// this is a pseudocode language intended to be interpreted and even written by LLM's. it is not strict language, just a set of conventions to define better agent behaviour 

// no functions here
// text is a prompt
hi, give me a poem // this is a prompt for the LLM to generate a poem 

x = 10 

how much is x? // this is a prompt for the LLM to answer the value of x

and how much is x + 5? // this is a prompt for the LLM to answer the value of x + 5

for file in ls -lahS:
    move file to <category>/ 
    example: mv file.jpg Pictures/ // this is a prompt for the LLM to move files to a specific category folder based on their type

"objects" and "classes" are just json notation

me = {
    name: Davi,
    age: 21,
    job: Student
}

I'm an adult? // this is a prompt for the LLM to determine if the user is an adult based on their age 

/*
btw, this is a multi-line comment 
comments are not intended to be seen by LLM's, they are removed before the prompt is sent to the LLM, so they are not part of the prompt.
*/

/*
I think that this is all the structure that I need to define my DSL? I guess?
basically we define vars with 
var = value 

for item in iterator/range/container:
    do something with item 

I forgot to mention control flow, but is the standard if/else statement
if condition:
    do something
else if another condition:
    do something else
else:
    do something else

btw, we can have type annotations too, but they are not really "official". like:

person: adult = {
    name: John
}

or 

person: engineer = {
    name: john 
}

answer: correct answer = some value to a question

btw, control flows can also be defined like this:

condition? do something. not condition? do something else.

that is also valid

condition? 
    do something.
not condition? 
    another condition?
        do something else.

[1, 2, 3, 4] is a list 

btw we can name things in a different way than = 

pi is 3.14 
me as user 

what is the value of pi? // this is a prompt for the LLM to answer the value of pi, it will probably not use the variable since it is a info very well know, but if it were other variable it would probably use it.

btw, since this is a flexible language, we can accept embbedded formats like json, yaml, xml, md, etc. just make sure to specify the format. you can use the type annotation for that btw 

data: yaml = 
    name: John
    age: 30
    city: New York

another data: toml = 
    name = "John"
    age = 30
    city = "New York"

other data: json = 
    {
        "name": "John",
        "age": 30,
        "city": "New York"
    }


I might add support to highlight syntax for editors later, but that is all that I will add for this language. it is not intended to be compiled, or something like that, so I will not make a lsp, nor a linter or type checker or anything too fancy. it is just a DSL to define prompts for LLM's, and to define some control flow and variables to make the prompts more dynamic.

maybe I can add a formatter actually, and a preprocessor to remove comments and "compile" to markdown, but that is all 

I said before that this language dont have functions, but why not?

fn name(args: type): type {
    do something
}

fn somebehaviour(parameters: text) {
    based on parameters, I want you to 
    do something.
}
*/

// this is intended to be the pseudocode language flavor of my language family. I dont know what to call it yet, I will think more about it later
// btw, I will probably need to make skills to LLM's interact better with this language, to write, review, understand and convert natural language to this language and vice versa. 
